skill.name: exploratory-data-analysis
skill.description: Perform comprehensive exploratory data analysis on scientific data files across 200+ file formats. This skill should be used when analyzing any scientific data file to understand its structure, content, quality, and characteristics. Automatically detects file type and generates detailed markdown reports with format-specific analysis, quality metrics, and downstream analysis recommendations. Covers chemistry, bioinformatics, microscopy, spectroscopy, proteomics, metabolomics, and general scientific data formats.

security_audit.summary: After thorough evaluation of 1063 static findings, all are false positives. The scanner misinterpreted Markdown code formatting (backticks) as shell commands, bioinformatics format names (SAM) as Windows credentials, and documentation references to hashing/checksums as weak cryptography. The skill is a legitimate scientific data analysis tool with no network access, no command execution, and no sensitive data handling.

content.value_statement: Understanding scientific data files requires specialized knowledge of hundreds of formats. This skill automatically detects file types, extracts relevant metadata and statistics, and generates comprehensive markdown reports with format-specific insights and downstream analysis recommendations.
actual_capabilities: Automatic detection of 200+ scientific file formats across 6 categories
Comprehensive metadata extraction including dimensions, data types, and quality metrics
Statistical analysis with distributions, summaries, and integrity checks
Detailed markdown report generation with format-specific documentation
Support for chemistry, bioinformatics, microscopy, spectroscopy, and general scientific formats
Recommendations for downstream analysis based on detected file type
limitations: Does not modify or transform input data files
Limited to reading files user explicitly provides
Analysis depth depends on available Python libraries for specific formats
Large files over several GB may require sampling for complete analysis

use_cases.title: Genomics data exploration
use_cases.description: Quickly understand structure and quality of sequence files, alignments, and variant calls before downstream analysis.

use_cases.title: Molecular data validation
use_cases.description: Validate molecular structure files, check data integrity, and prepare for computational chemistry workflows.

use_cases.title: Scientific data onboarding
use_cases.description: Automatically document unknown or legacy scientific data formats for team knowledge sharing and compliance.

prompt_templates.title: Basic file analysis
prompt_templates.prompt: Use the exploratory-data-analysis skill to analyze this file: {file_path}. Report the file type, structure, and key statistics.

prompt_templates.title: Quality assessment
prompt_templates.prompt: Analyze the quality and completeness of {file_path} using exploratory-data-analysis. What issues should I address before downstream analysis?

prompt_templates.title: Format documentation
prompt_templates.prompt: Use exploratory-data-analysis to generate a comprehensive report for {file_path} including format documentation and analysis recommendations.

prompt_templates.title: Batch exploration
prompt_templates.prompt: Analyze all scientific data files in directory {path} using exploratory-data-analysis. Provide a summary of each file type and recommendations for processing them.

output: Columns: sample_id, treatment, concentration, absorbance, fluorescence, time_point, temperature, replicate, batch, operator, date, notes
Data Quality: 3 missing values in 'operator' column (0.4%)
Numeric columns show normal distribution for most metrics
Recommendation: Consider imputing missing operator values before analysis

best_practices: Provide the full file path to ensure accurate analysis
Review the generated report before proceeding with downstream analysis
Use the quality metrics to identify data cleaning needs early
Save reports for documentation and reproducibility purposes
anti_patterns: Do not use for analyzing files that require specialized domain knowledge beyond basic statistics
Avoid analyzing files in read-only directories without write permissions for reports
Do not expect transformation or conversion of file formats
Avoid assuming complete analysis without reviewing the markdown report

faq.question: What scientific formats are supported?
faq.answer: Supports 200+ formats including PDB, FASTA, FASTQ, SAM, BAM, VCF, TIFF, DICOM, NMR, Mass Spec files, and more.

faq.question: Does this modify my data files?
faq.answer: No, the skill only reads files to analyze them. No modifications are made to source data.

faq.question: How large files are supported?
faq.answer: Large files are sampled (typically first 10k rows) for analysis to maintain performance. Full analysis requires sufficient memory.

faq.question: What libraries are used?
faq.answer: Uses Biopython, NumPy, Pandas, h5py, and other scientific libraries depending on file format.

faq.question: Can I analyze multiple files at once?
faq.answer: Each invocation analyzes one file. For multiple files, call the skill separately for each file path.

faq.question: Where are reports saved?
faq.answer: Reports print to stdout by default. Use output_path parameter to save as markdown files.
